{
  "local_port": 36270,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can you locate the name of a proxy server?",
  "response": "Locating the name of a proxy server depends on the context and the system you're using. Here are common methods to identify a proxy server:\n\n### 1. **Check Browser Settings**\n   - **Google Chrome**:  \n     Go to `Settings` > `System` > `Open your computer's proxy settings` (or directly type `chrome://settings/system` in the address bar).  \n     On Windows, this opens the **Internet Properties** dialog where you can view the proxy settings under the **Connections** tab > **LAN settings**.\n   - **Mozilla Firefox**:  \n     Go to `Settings` > `General` > `Network Settings` > `Settings`. Look for \"Manual proxy configuration\" or \"Auto-detect proxy settings.\"\n   - **Microsoft Edge**:  \n     Go to `Settings` > `System and Performance` > `Open your computer's proxy settings`. This will redirect you to the system proxy settings.\n\n### 2. **Check System-Wide Proxy Settings**\n   - **Windows**:  \n     Open `Settings` > `Network & Internet` > `Proxy`. Look for the \"Manual proxy setup\" section or \"Automatic proxy setup\" to find the proxy server name.\n   - **macOS**:  \n     Go to `System Preferences` > `Network` > Select your active network (e.g., Wi-Fi) > `Advanced` > `Proxies`. Look for \"Web Proxy (HTTP)\" or \"Secure Web Proxy (HTTPS)\" to find the proxy server name.\n   - **Linux**:  \n     Depending on your desktop environment, check network settings or use the terminal to check environment variables like `http_proxy` or `https_proxy`:\n     ```bash\n     echo $http_proxy\n     echo $https_proxy\n     ```\n\n### 3. **Check Network Configuration Files**\n   - On Linux or macOS, proxy settings might be configured in system files like `/etc/environment`, `/etc/profile`, or `/etc/apt/apt.conf`. Search for `http_proxy` or `https_proxy` in these files.\n\n### 4. **Check Environment Variables**\n   - On Linux, macOS, or Windows, you can check environment variables for proxy settings:\n     ```bash\n     echo $http_proxy\n     echo $https_proxy\n     ```\n   - On Windows, use Command Prompt:\n     ```cmd\n     echo %http_proxy%\n     echo %https_proxy%\n     ```\n\n### 5. **Check Corporate or Organization Settings**\n   - If you're on a corporate network, the proxy server might be configured by your IT department. Contact your network administrator for details.\n\n### 6. **Use Online Tools**\n   - Websites like [WhatIsMyIP](https://www.whatismyip.com/) or [IPLeak](https://ipleak.net/) can detect if you're using a proxy and provide information about it.\n\n### 7. **Browser Developer Tools**\n   - Open the browser's developer tools (F12), go to the `Network` tab, and inspect requests. Look for the `proxy` or `via` headers to identify the proxy.\n\n### 8. **Check Proxy Configuration Scripts**\n   - Some networks use a Proxy Auto-Configuration (PAC) file. Check the PAC file URL in your browser or system settings, and inspect the file for the proxy server name.\n\n### 9. **Ask Your ISP or Administrator**\n   - If you're unsure, your Internet Service Provider (ISP) or network administrator can provide the proxy server details.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to identify the name of the proxy server being used on your system or network.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
